{{wpv-no-posts-found}}{{wpml-string context=&quot;wpv-views&quot;}}&lt;strong&gt;No posts found&lt;/strong&gt;{{/wpml-string}}{{/wpv-no-posts-found}}
{{wpv-layout-end}}

[/html]

The {{wpv-if}} shortcode checks for conditional statements within your View. This makes use of the featured_level custom field which you should have already created.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3645" title="Conditional shortcodes" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/conditionalshortcode3.png" alt="The HTML box with the code inserted. The conditional tag that checks for gold is highlighted with a callout image of the Level post meta, and the silver conditional tag is highlighted with a callout image of the Level post meta" />

Here is the conditional shortcode wrapped in HTML:

[html]
&lt;div class=&quot;classified_featured_wrapper {{wpv-if level=&quot;wpcf-featured_level&quot; evaluate=&quot;$level = 'silver'&quot;}}silver{{/wpv-if}}{{wpv-if level=&quot;wpcf-featured_level&quot; evaluate=&quot;$level = 'gold'&quot;}}gold{{/wpv-if}}&quot;&gt;{{wpv-post-featured-image}}&lt;div class=&quot;classified_featured_title&quot;&gt;{{wpv-post-link}}&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
[/html]

Let's break it down. The shortcode is doing the following:
<ul>
	<li><strong>IF</strong> the featured level is set to silver, <strong>display </strong>using the classified_featured_wrapper silver div</li>
	<li><strong>IF</strong> the featured level is set to gold, <strong>display </strong>using the classified_featured_wrapper gold div</li>
</ul>
<a href="/?page_id=3440">To learn more about what you can do with the conditional shortcode, check out this tutorial.</a>

When you're ready click Publish.
<h2>2. Create the Homepage Classifieds Lists</h2>
Next we'll create the main Classifieds Lists that will be displayed on the homepage. This consists of a Taxonomy View within a Taxonomy View.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3645" title="Classified Ads Taxonomy Views" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/classifiedads1.png" alt="A screenshot of the classified ads on the classified theme. The main headings are highlighted with the message The Classifieds Category Taxonomy View is the parent View. It outputs the main lists. The list items are highlighted with the message The Classifieds Subcategories Taxonomy View outputs the sub-category items based on the parent view." />

Let's start of by creating the sub-category View, which will be the child.
<h3>a) Create the Classified Subcategories View</h3>
Navigate to <strong>Views &gt; Add New View</strong>

Call the View &quot;Classified Subcategories View&quot;.
<h4>Filter the Content</h4>
For the first Filter, filter by Taxonomy and select Categories. You should set the settings as follows:
<ul>
	<li>Don't show empty terms - <strong>uncheck</strong></li>
	<li>Include terms that have non-empty descendents - <strong>uncheck </strong></li>
	<li>Include children in the post count - <strong>check</strong></li>
</ul>
Make sure you order by name, descending.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3645" title="Classifieds Subcategories filter" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/subcategoriesfilter1.png" alt="A screenshot of the filter, as set up above." />

Click &quot;Add Another Filter Term&quot;.

Select to <strong>filter by Taxonomy parent</strong> and check the box that says &quot;Parent is the taxonomy selected by the parent view&quot;. This will make sure that the results are filtered based on the category from the parent View (which we'll create in the next step).

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3645" title="Classifieds Subcategories add another filter" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/subcategoriesfilter2.png" alt="A screenshot of the filter, as set up above." />
<h4>Layout Your Content</h4>
From the layout style dropdown select <strong>unordered </strong>list. Add the following fields:
<ul>
	<li>Taxonomy link with a Title</li>
	<li>Taxonomy post count</li>
</ul>
<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3645" title="Classifieds Subcategories layout" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/subcategorieslayout1.png" alt="A screenshot of the layout, as set up above." />

All we need to add to the HTML are some brackets to separate our post count from the taxonomy term name.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3839" title="brackets" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/brackets.png" alt="the list as displayed on the front end with the post count in brackets" width="469" height="107" />

Click &quot;View/Edit Meta HTML&quot;.

Edit the HTML to the following:

[html]
{{wpv-layout-start}}
&lt;!-- wpv-loop-start --&gt;
 &lt;ul&gt;
 &lt;wpv-loop&gt;
 &lt;li&gt;{{wpv-taxonomy-link}} ({{wpv-taxonomy-post-count}})&lt;/li&gt;
 &lt;/wpv-loop&gt;
 &lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;!-- wpv-loop-end --&gt;
{{wpv-no-taxonomy-found}}{{wpml-string context=&quot;wpv-views&quot;}}&lt;strong&gt;No taxonomy found&lt;/strong&gt;{{/wpml-string}}{{/wpv-no-taxonomy-found}}
{{wpv-layout-end}}
[/html]

When you're done click Publish.
<h3>b) Create the Classified Categories View</h3>
The main Categories View will output the lists on the homepage. It returns a taxonomy, and include the subcategories View which <strong>outputs a list based on the parent taxonomy</strong>.

To create the View navigate toViews &gt; Add New View.

Call your View &quot;Classified Categories View&quot;.
<h4>Filter the Content</h4>
For the first Filter, filter by Taxonomy and select Categories. You should set the settings as follows:
<ul>
	<li>Don't show empty terms - <strong>uncheck</strong></li>
	<li>Include terms that have non-empty descendents - <strong>uncheck</strong></li>
	<li>Include children in the post count - <strong>check</strong></li>
</ul>
Make sure you order by name, descending.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3645" title="Classifieds Subcategories filter" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/subcategoriesfilter1.png" alt="A screenshot of the filter, as set up above." />

Click <strong>Add Another Filter Term</strong>. From the dropdown select &quot;<strong>Taxonomy Term</strong>&quot; and then <strong>select the Taxonomy terms you would like to display on the homepage</strong>. On our demo we have selected Business, Sport, Technology, Tutorials, World.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3645" title="Classifieds Categories add another filter" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/categoriesfilter2.png" alt="A screenshot of the filter, as set up above." />
<h4>Display the Content</h4>
Choose the Table layout style, with Four columns. Add the following fields:
<ul>
	<li>Taxonomy title with a link</li>
	<li>Classified Subcategories View - Taxonomy View</li>
</ul>
We've added some styles to the layout:

[html]
{{wpv-layout-start}}
&lt;!-- wpv-loop-start --&gt;
&lt;div id=&quot;classifieds_view_wrapper&quot;&gt;
 &lt;table width=&quot;100%&quot;&gt;
 &lt;wpv-loop wrap=&quot;4&quot; pad=&quot;true&quot;&gt;
 {{wpv-item index=1}}
 &lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;classifieds_parent_wrap&quot;&gt;&lt;h3 class=&quot;classifieds_parent_title&quot;&gt;{{wpv-taxonomy-link}} ( {{wpv-taxonomy-post-count}} ) &lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;classifieds_parent_content&quot;&gt; {{wpv-view name=&quot;Classified Subcategories View&quot;}} &lt;/div&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;/td&gt;
 {{wpv-item index=other}}
 &lt;td&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;classifieds_parent_wrap&quot;&gt;&lt;h3 class=&quot;classifieds_parent_title&quot;&gt;{{wpv-taxonomy-link}} ( {{wpv-taxonomy-post-count}} ) &lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;classifieds_parent_content&quot;&gt; {{wpv-view name=&quot;Classified Subcategories View&quot;}} &lt;/div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
 {{wpv-item index=4}}
 &lt;td&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;classifieds_parent_wrap&quot;&gt;&lt;h3 class=&quot;classifieds_parent_title&quot;&gt;{{wpv-taxonomy-link}} ( {{wpv-taxonomy-post-count}} ) &lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;classifieds_parent_content&quot;&gt; {{wpv-view name=&quot;Classified Subcategories View&quot;}} &lt;/div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
 &lt;/wpv-loop&gt;
 &lt;/table&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;!-- wpv-loop-end --&gt;
{{wpv-no-taxonomy-found}}{{wpml-string context=&quot;wpv-views&quot;}}&lt;strong&gt;No taxonomy found&lt;/strong&gt;{{/wpml-string}}{{/wpv-no-taxonomy-found}}
{{wpv-layout-end}}

[/html]

Click Publish.
<h3>3. Insert the Content</h3>
Now it's time to <strong>insert the Views into the homepage</strong>. Navigate to Pages &gt; All Pages and click the edit button underneath the name of the homepage.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3645" title="edit the homepage" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/edithome.png" alt="the homepage on the All pages page. A mouse pointer hovers over the edit button." />

To insert the shortcodes click on the Views icon and select the featured ad shortcode and the Classifieds Category View shortcode.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3645" title="Insert views shortcodes" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/insertviewsshortcode.png" alt="The insert views icon with the insert views shortcode popup. The Features Ads Levels View and the Classifieds Categories View are selected." />

You can <strong>add content around the shortcodes</strong>.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3645" title="shortcodes" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/shortcodes.png" alt="The homepage text area with the shortcodes and other text inserted" />

Click Publish.

<strong>Your WordPress Classifieds Theme is good to go!</strong> Just add some content and you've got a powerful Classifieds directory, and you've written no code at all!

Classifieds Listings can be an excellent resource for people who are looking for particular products or services. This makes them a popular type of WordPress Theme. This tutorial will show you how to use the Views plugin to create a <strong><a href="http://ref.wp-types.com/classifieds/" rel="external nofollow">WordPress Classifieds Site</a></strong>. You'll learn how to use Views to produce complex lists. In this tutorial you'll also learn how to use the <strong> Views conditional shortcode</strong> to control the HTML output based on the post content.

To create a WordPress Classifieds Theme you need to pull data from the WordPress database, and display it in lists - which Views is perfect for doing!

Before we get started, please use the <a href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/types/">Types plugin</a> to create the following Custom Fields:
<ul>
	<li><strong>Featured Ad</strong> - checkbox field (value to store set to &quot;1&quot;)</li>
	<li><strong>Featured Level</strong> - textfield field</li>
</ul>
Make sure that you have set a static front page under <strong>Reading &gt; Settings.</strong>

Here's how the final Classifieds site will look:

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3645" title="classifieds" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/classifieds1.png" alt="a screenshot of the classifieds theme homepage" />

Here's a schema of how it works:

<ta_ignore>[caption id="attachment_3798" align="aligncenter" width="706" caption="</ta_ignore>A schema of the Classifieds WordPress Theme made with Views<ta_ignore>"]</ta_ignore><img class="size-full wp-image-3798" title="schema" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/schema1.png" alt="a schema for the classifieds wordpress theme" width="706" height="506" /><ta_ignore>[/caption]</ta_ignore>

These are the steps we will take:
<ol>
	<li>Create the Featured Bar</li>
	<li>Create the Homepage Classifieds lists</li>
	<li>Insert the Content</li>
</ol>
[box type=&quot;info&quot;] <strong>Pro Tip!</strong> If you want to extend your Classifieds site even further you could use Custom Post Types to create different types of content, and use View Templates to create layouts for your Classified adverts. [/box]

You will need to add the following to your theme's style.css. You can amend and make tweaks to it all you want.

[css]
/**
* Specific Classifieds styling changes
*
*/

#classifieds_view_wrapper table td {
 vertical-align: top;
 width: 25%;
}

#classifieds_view_wrapper .classifieds_parent_title {
 font-weight: bold;
 font-size: 16px;
 color: #616D8B;
 padding-bottom: 5px;
 margin-bottom: 5px;
 border-bottom: 1px black solid;
}

#classifieds_view_wrapper .classifieds_parent_wrapper {
 margin: 0px 4px;
}

#classifieds_view_wrapper ul li {
 list-style: circle;
}

.classified_featured_wrapper {
 text-align: center;
 padding: 5px 0px;
}

#classified_featured_ads table td{
 width: 180px;
 vertical-align: top;
}

#classified_featured_ads .classified_featured_title {
 vertical-align: top;
 width: 150px;
 font-style: italic;
 height: 40px;
}

#classified_featured_ads .classified_featured_title a {
 font-weight: italic;
 font-size: 13px;
}

h3.classifieds_heading {
 font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;, Times, serif;
 font-size: 20px;
 font-weight: bold;
 color: #444444;
 margin: 20px 0px;
}

#classified_featured_ads .silver {
 background-color: #F5F5F5;
}

#classified_featured_ads .gold {
 background-color: #FFEC8B;
}
[/css]
<h2>1. Create the Featured Bar</h2>
The Featured Bar on the homepage is created using a View. The View filters for content that has been marked as Featured using your custom fields.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3645" title="Featured Ad Banner" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/featuredad1.png" alt="a screenshot of the featured listing banner - it is circled and marked as a Post View" />

It then uses the Views conditional shortcode to <strong>check for the membership level and output accordingly</strong>.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3645" title="Conditional shortcode" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/conditionalshortcode.png" alt="The featured posts on the two ends are highlighted. One has a silver box around it, the other a gold. They have both been output using the wpv-if shortcode" />

Let's set it up.

Navigate to <strong>Views &gt; Add New View</strong>

Call the View &quot;Featured Ads Levels View&quot;

[box type=&quot;info]There are two shortcodes in the text area. <strong>Do not remove these</strong>. They are needed to output the View.[/box]
<h3>Filter Your Content</h3>
Start by filtering your content. Click on the Edit button under Filter and select to filter Posts, by post date, in a descending order.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3645" title="Featured Ads filter" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/filterfeaturedads1.png" alt="The filter settings for the featured bar. The above settings are highlighted." />

Next, click <strong>Add Another Filter Term</strong>. This time you should filter by custom field <strong>wpcf-featured-level</strong>. You should have already created this using Types. If you haven't, please return to the top of the tutorial to see the list of custom fields you need to create.

For the comparison function select = <strong>numeric</strong>.

Set the <strong>value to compare to 1.</strong>

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3645" title="Featured Ads 2nd filter" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/filterfeaturedads2.png" alt="The add another filter popup with the above settings." />

This will check for posts that have a mark in the checkbox in the Featured Level custom field in the edit post screen. Like this one:

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3645" title="Featured Ads checkbox" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/featuredadcheckbox.png" alt="The featured ad checkbox on the post editing screen. The box has been checked" />

If the post has been marked as a featured ad it will display, if it hasn't, it will not.
<h3>Display Your Content</h3>
Now to lay your content out. From the layout style dropdown select <strong>table</strong> and give the table 5 columns. This will mean that 5 items will display along a row.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3645" title="Featured Ad filter" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/featuredadslayout1.png" alt="The view layout with the style set to table with five columns" />
<h3>Using the Conditional Shortcode</h3>
Now it's time to use the <strong>wpv conditional shortcode to display posts that have gold or silver membership with a different background</strong>. To do this click <strong>View/Edit Meta HTML</strong>.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3645" title="View Edit Meta HTML" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/featuredadviewedithtml.png" alt="The View Edit HTML link" />

Here's what the code looks like:

[html]
{{wpv-layout-start}}
&lt;!-- wpv-loop-start --&gt;
&lt;div id=&quot;classified_featured_ads&quot;&gt;
 &lt;table width=&quot;100%&quot;&gt;
 &lt;wpv-loop wrap=&quot;5&quot; pad=&quot;true&quot;&gt;
 {{wpv-item index=1}}
 &lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;classified_featured_wrapper {{wpv-if level=&quot;wpcf-featured_level&quot; evaluate=&quot;$level = 'silver'&quot;}}silver{{/wpv-if}}{{wpv-if level=&quot;wpcf-featured_level&quot; evaluate=&quot;$level = 'gold'&quot;}}gold{{/wpv-if}}&quot;&gt;{{wpv-post-featured-image}}&lt;div class=&quot;classified_featured_title&quot;&gt;{{wpv-post-link}}&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
 {{wpv-item index=other}}
 &lt;td&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;classified_featured_wrapper {{wpv-if level=&quot;wpcf-featured_level&quot; evaluate=&quot;$level = 'silver'&quot;}}silver{{/wpv-if}}{{wpv-if level=&quot;wpcf-featured_level&quot; evaluate=&quot;$level = 'gold'&quot;}}gold{{/wpv-if}}&quot;&gt;{{wpv-post-featured-image}}&lt;div class=&quot;classified_featured_title&quot;&gt;{{wpv-post-link}}&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
 {{wpv-item index=5}}
 &lt;td&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;classified_featured_wrapper {{wpv-if level=&quot;wpcf-featured_level&quot; evaluate=&quot;$level = 'silver'&quot;}}silver{{/wpv-if}}{{wpv-if level=&quot;wpcf-featured_level&quot; evaluate=&quot;$level = 'gold'&quot;}}gold{{/wpv-if}}&quot;&gt;{{wpv-post-featured-image}}&lt;div class=&quot;classified_featured_title&quot;&gt;{{wpv-post-link}}&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
 &lt;/wpv-loop&gt;
 &lt;/table&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- wpv-loop-end --&gt;
{{wpv-no-posts-found}}{{wpml-string context=&quot;wpv-views&quot;}}&lt;strong&gt;No posts found&lt;/strong&gt;{{/wpml-string}}{{/wpv-no-posts-found}}
{{wpv-layout-end}}

[/html]

The {{wpv-if}} shortcode checks for conditional statements within your View. This makes use of the featured_level custom field which you should have already created.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3645" title="Conditional shortcodes" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/conditionalshortcode3.png" alt="The HTML box with the code inserted. The conditional tag that checks for gold is highlighted with a callout image of the Level post meta, and the silver conditional tag is highlighted with a callout image of the Level post meta" />

Here is the conditional shortcode wrapped in HTML:

[html]
&lt;div class=&quot;classified_featured_wrapper {{wpv-if level=&quot;wpcf-featured_level&quot; evaluate=&quot;$level = 'silver'&quot;}}silver{{/wpv-if}}{{wpv-if level=&quot;wpcf-featured_level&quot; evaluate=&quot;$level = 'gold'&quot;}}gold{{/wpv-if}}&quot;&gt;{{wpv-post-featured-image}}&lt;div class=&quot;classified_featured_title&quot;&gt;{{wpv-post-link}}&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
[/html]

Let's break it down. The shortcode is doing the following:
<ul>
	<li><strong>IF</strong> the featured level is set to silver, <strong>display </strong>using the classified_featured_wrapper silver div</li>
	<li><strong>IF</strong> the featured level is set to gold, <strong>display </strong>using the classified_featured_wrapper gold div</li>
</ul>
<a href="/?page_id=3440">To learn more about what you can do with the conditional shortcode, check out this tutorial.</a>

When you're ready click Publish.
<h2>2. Create the Homepage Classifieds Lists</h2>
Next we'll create the main Classifieds Lists that will be displayed on the homepage. This consists of a Taxonomy View within a Taxonomy View.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3645" title="Classified Ads Taxonomy Views" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/classifiedads1.png" alt="A screenshot of the classified ads on the classified theme. The main headings are highlighted with the message The Classifieds Category Taxonomy View is the parent View. It outputs the main lists. The list items are highlighted with the message The Classifieds Subcategories Taxonomy View outputs the sub-category items based on the parent view." />

