}
[/code]</ta_ignore>

You will also need to use the <a href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/types/">Types plugin</a> to create a <strong>custom field which should be attached to posts</strong>. This custom field should be an <strong>image field</strong> called Magazine Image. <a href="/?page_id=254">If you are unsure of what custom fields are you can read about them here.</a>

[box type=&rdquo;info&rdquo;]Ensure that you have set a static front page. You can do this under Settings &gt; Reading.[/box]

In this tutorial we will carry out the following steps:
<ol>
	<li>Create Three View Templates</li>
	<li>Create the Main Content Area</li>
	<li>Create a Slider</li>
	<li>Create a Sidebar</li>
	<li>Show your Views</li>
</ol>
Let&rsquo;s get started:
<h2>1) Create Three View Templates</h2>
You need to create three View Templates which will be displayed in our Views. You can <strong>display View Templates within Views to make more complex layouts</strong>. The View Template determines the layout for an individual piece of content, and a View queries the database and lays out groups of content and lists.

You will be creating View Templates for each of the areas of the homepage:
<ul>
	<li>Main body &ndash; i.e. post listing</li>
	<li>Slider</li>
	<li>Sidebar</li>
</ul>
To create a View Template navigate to <strong>Views &gt; Add New View Template</strong>
<h3>a) Create the Post Listing View Template</h3>
The Post Listing View Template provides the <strong>layout for individual items on the main body of the homepage</strong>. We want to display the <strong>post title with URL</strong>, the <strong>featured image</strong> and the <strong>post excerpt</strong>.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3583" title="post listing view template" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/postlistingviewtemplate.png" alt="an image of a single post listing on the front page. The image, excerpt and post title are highlighted" />

To insert a shortcode into the View Template click on the <strong>Views icon</strong> on the Add New View Template admin page.

<img class="aligncenter size-full" title="insert the shortcodes" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/insertshortcode.png" alt="an image the views icon with the shortcode popup. The title with link, excerpt and featured image shortcodes are highlighted" />

Here you can select the shortcodes you wish to display. <strong>Insert</strong> them into the text area and <strong>wrap them in some styles</strong>.

<ta_ignore>[code]
&lt;div class=&quot;magazine_post&quot;&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;magazine_post_featured&quot;&gt;{{wpv-post-featured-image}}&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class=&quot;magazine_post_title&quot;&gt;{{wpv-post-link}}&lt;/div&gt;
       &lt;div class=&quot;magazine_post_excerpt&quot;&gt;{{wpv-post-excerpt length=&quot;100&quot;}}&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt; &lt;!-- end #magazine_post --&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;clear&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
[/code]</ta_ignore>

Beside the text area under View Template Settings select &ldquo;<strong>Raw output</strong>&rdquo;. This will prevent WordPress from adding line breaks and paragraphs.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3583" title="view template settings" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/viewtemplatesettings.png" alt="the View Template settings with the Raw output option highlighted" />

When you&rsquo;re done click <strong>Publish</strong>.
<h3>b) Create the Slider View Template</h3>
The Slider View Template will display the <strong>magazine image custom field</strong> that you should already have created, along with the <strong>post title</strong>. This time you need to display the magazine image custom field that you have already created, and the post title with URL.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3583" title="homepage slider" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/viewtemplateslider.png" alt="a screenshot of the view template slider" />

Again let&rsquo;s wrap it in some divs.

<ta_ignore>[code]
&lt;div class=&quot;magazine_slide&quot;&gt;
&lt;h3 class=&quot;slider_title&quot;&gt;{{wpv-post-link}}&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;div&gt;{{types field=&quot;magazine-image&quot; width=&quot;600&quot; proportional=&quot;true&quot; align=&quot;none&quot;}}&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
[/code]</ta_ignore>

And select <strong>Raw Output </strong>under the View Template settings.

Click <strong>Publish</strong>.
<h3>c) Create the Sidebar View Template</h3>
The Sidebar View Template will provide the <strong>layout for items appearing in the sidebar widget</strong>. This will display the Featured Image, the Post Title with URL and the excerpt.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3583" title="post listing view template" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/postlistingviewtemplate.png" alt="an image of a post in the sidebar on the front page. The image, excerpt and post title are highlighted" />

Here are the shortcodes, wrapped in some divs.

<ta_ignore>[code]
&lt;div class=&quot;magazine_post&quot;&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;magazine_post_featured&quot;&gt;{{wpv-post-featured-image}}&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class=&quot;magazine_post_title&quot;&gt;{{wpv-post-link}}&lt;/div&gt;
       &lt;div class=&quot;magazine_post_excerpt&quot;&gt;{{wpv-post-excerpt length=&quot;80&quot;}}&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt; &lt;!-- end #magazine_post --&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;clear&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
[/code]</ta_ignore>


Again, select <strong>Raw Output</strong> from the View Template Settings.

Click <strong>Publish</strong>.

We now need to create four Views. These will grab the content and lay out the following:
<ul>
	<li>The <strong>sidebar</strong></li>
	<li>The <strong>slider</strong></li>
	<li>The <strong>main content section</strong></li>
	<li>Each individual <strong>column</strong> in the main content section</li>
</ul>
<h2>2) Create the Main Content Area</h2>
The main content area is created using a <strong>View within a View</strong>. The parent View will query the WordPress database for a specific taxonomy, the View inside it will filter for posts with each particular category term.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3578" title="maincontentarea" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/maincontentarea.png" alt="an image of the main content area on the homepage. There are four columns, each filtering with an individual taxonomy. All four columns are circled with the caption 'Created with a View that queries for a taxonomy'. A single column is circled with the caption 'created with a view that queries for posts categorized by a specific term within that taxonomy'" width="599" height="616" />

First of all we will create the View that grabs the posts from the database, then we&rsquo;ll place it within the View that filters taxonomies.
<h3>a) Create a View that Returns Posts</h3>
Navigate to <strong>Views &gt; Add New View</strong>.

Call your View &ldquo;Category Posts Listing.&rdquo;

[box type=&rdquo;info&rdquo;]Note: When you create a View there are two shortcodes in the text area. These filter the content and lay out the content. <strong>You should not remove these</strong>.[/box]
<h4>Filter Your Content</h4>
Scroll down to Filter and select Posts, order by post date, descending.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3583" title="post filter" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/categorypostslistingfilter.png" alt="a screenshot of the post filter" />

Then select Add Another Filter Term. From the <strong>Select What to Filter By</strong> dropdown select <strong>Categories</strong>, and from the <strong>Condition </strong>dropdown select <strong>Value set by Parent View</strong>.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3583" title="add another filter popup" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/categorypostslistingfilter2.png" alt="a screenshot of the add another filter popup" />
<h4>Create Your Layout</h4>
From the Layout Style dropdown list select <strong>Unordered List.</strong>

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3583" title="unordered list" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/categorypostslistinglayout1.png" alt="a screenshot of the layout style dropdown. The mouse hovers over the unordered list item" />

Now click Add Field. You should select <strong>Title with a Link</strong> and <strong>Featured Image</strong>.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3583" title="add a field group" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/categorypostslistinglayout2.png" alt="the add field popup. The Title with a Link and Feature Image items are highlighted" />

Click Publish.
<h3>b) Create a View that Returns Taxonomies.</h3>
Now to create the parent View. Navigate to View &gt; Add New View.

Call it &ldquo;Categories View&rdquo;.
<h4>Filter the View</h4>
This time, select <strong>Taxonomy </strong>for your first filter.

Select Categories for the type of taxonomy, and check Don&rsquo;t show empty terms, and Include terms that have non-empty descendents.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3583" title="query taxonomy" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/categoriesviewfilter1.png" alt="a screenshot of the View Query Filter setup with Taxonomy highlighted" />

Click Add another filter term, select <strong>taxonomy term</strong> from the dropdown and select the <strong>categories you wish to display</strong> in the main content area on the homepage.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3583" title="add another filter term" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/categoriesviewfilter2.png" alt="a screenshot of the add another filter term popup" />
<h4>Create Your Layout</h4>
Now to create the layout. This time choose the <strong>table layout style</strong>.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3583" title="view layout dropdown" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/categoriesviewlayout1.png" alt="a screenshot of the View layout, layout style dropdown" />

Add Field and select <strong>Taxonomy Title</strong> and <strong>Categories Posts Listing</strong>. This will insert the View that you already created inside this Taxonomy View.

<img src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/categoriespostlisting.png" alt="he add a taxonomy field popup with taxonomy title and categories view highlighted" title="categoriespostlisting" width="614" height="237" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-4104" />

Now click on <strong>View/Edit Meta HTML</strong>.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3609" title="add edit html" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/categoriesviewlayout3.png" alt="the add/edit meta html link" width="272" height="116" />

Here you can style your layout. We&rsquo;ve wrapped the shortcodes in the styles I provided you with at the start of the tutorial.

<ta_ignore>[code]
{{wpv-layout-start}}
&lt;!-- wpv-loop-start --&gt;
&lt;div id=&quot;magazine_view_wrapper&quot;&gt;
   &lt;table width=&quot;100%&quot;&gt;
      &lt;wpv-loop wrap=&quot;2&quot; pad=&quot;true&quot;&gt;
      {{wpv-item index=1}}
            &lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;&lt;h3 class=&quot;magazine_list_title&quot;&gt;{{wpv-taxonomy-link}}&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;magazine_list_content&quot;&gt;{{wpv-view name=&quot;Category Posts Listing&quot;}}&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
         {{wpv-item index=other}}
            &lt;td&gt;&lt;h3 class=&quot;magazine_list_title&quot;&gt;{{wpv-taxonomy-link}}&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;magazine_list_content&quot;&gt;{{wpv-view name=&quot;Category Posts Listing&quot;}}&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
         {{wpv-item index=2}}
            &lt;td&gt;&lt;h3 class=&quot;magazine_list_title&quot;&gt;{{wpv-taxonomy-link}}&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;magazine_list_content&quot;&gt;{{wpv-view name=&quot;Category Posts Listing&quot;}}&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
      &lt;/wpv-loop&gt;
   &lt;/table&gt;
&lt;/div&gt; &lt;!-- end of #magazine_view_wrapper --&gt;
&lt;!-- wpv-loop-end --&gt;
{{wpv-no-taxonomy-found}}{{wpml-string context=&quot;wpv-views&quot;}}&lt;strong&gt;No taxonomy found&lt;/strong&gt;{{/wpml-string}}{{/wpv-no-taxonomy-found}}
{{wpv-layout-end}}
[/code]</ta_ignore>

Click Save View.
<h3>3) Create the Homepage Slider</h3>
It&rsquo;s time to create the slider for your homepage. To do this navigate to <strong>Views &gt; Add New View</strong>.

Call your View &ldquo;Slider View&rdquo;.
<h4>Filter Your Content</h4>
This time select <strong>All Post Types</strong>, ordered by <strong>post date, descending</strong>.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3583" title="filter options" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/sliderviewlayout1.png" alt="the filter options" />

Click Add Another Filter and select <strong>Categories </strong>from the first dropdown. Under the Condition dropdown select Post is: &ldquo;<strong>Any of the following</strong>&rdquo;. Choose the <strong>Category you wish to display in the slider</strong> &ndash; in this case I&rsquo;ve chosen World.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3583" title="post listing view template" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/sliderviewlayout2.png" alt="the add another filter term popup" />
<h4>Set Pagination</h4>
You need to enable pagination. Views has built-in <strong>auto-transitions</strong> so that you can <a title="WordPress Sliders" href="/?page_id=1272">easily create a slider</a>. Click the Edit button beside pagination. Select <strong>Auto-transition</strong> from the dropdown, display <strong>1 item per page</strong>, show each page for <strong>4 seconds</strong>, and <strong>slide left</strong>. You should check the boxes beside:
<ul>
	<li>Preload images before transition</li>
	<li>Cache pages</li>
	<li>Pre-load the next and previous pages</li>
	<li>No spinner graphics</li>
</ul>
<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3583" title="pagination options" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/sliderviewpagination.png" alt="an image of the pagination options with the above settings" />
<h4>Create Your Layout</h4>
From the layout style dropdown select <strong>Unformatted</strong>. Then click <strong>Add Field</strong> and insert <strong>Slider View Template</strong>. This will display the View Template that we already created for the slider. <a href="/?page_id=548">You can read more about creating complex layouts by inserting View Templates into a View.</a>

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3583" title="slider view layout" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/sliderviewlayout.png" alt="an image of the view layout options with an unformatted layout and the slider view template inserted" />

Click <strong>Publish</strong>.
<h3>4) Create the Sidebar Content</h3>
To add content to the sidebar, you need to create a <strong>View that displays the Sidebar View Template</strong>. Then you can add a widget to the sidebar. To get started navigate to Views &gt; Add New View.

Call your View &quot;Sidebar View&quot;.
<h4>Filter Your Content</h4>
The sidebar should <strong>display posts in a specific category</strong>. First of all, filter for <strong>Posts</strong>, by <strong>post date</strong>, <strong>descending</strong>.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3583" title="sidebar view filter" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/sidebarviewfilter1.png" alt="an image of the filter options with the above options selected" />

Add another filter. This time select to filter by <strong>Categories</strong>, set the condition to Post is <strong>Any of the following</strong>, and select the <strong>category </strong>you would like to display in the sidebar.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3583" title="sidebar filter categories" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/sidebarviewfilter2.png" alt="an image of the add another filter term popup with the above settings" />
<h4>Create Your Layout</h4>
From the View layout dropdown select <strong>Unformatted </strong>and add the <strong>Sidebar View Template</strong> field. This will display the sidebar View Template that you created earlier.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3583" title="sidebar layout" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/sidebarviewlayout1.png" alt="a screenshot of the sidebar view layout settings with the layout set to unformatted, displaying the sidebar view template" />

Now to <strong>add some styles</strong> to the layout. Click View/Edit Meta HTML.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3583" title="edit html" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/sidebarviewlayout2.png" alt="the view/edit meta html link" />

Below is the code. You can see where the shortcodes have been wrapped in divs.

<ta_ignore>[code]
{{wpv-layout-start}}
&lt;!-- wpv-loop-start --&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;magazine_posts_list&quot;&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;magazine_list_content&quot;&gt;
   &lt;wpv-loop&gt;
      {{wpv-post-body view_template=&quot;sidebar-view-template&quot;}}
   &lt;/wpv-loop&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;!-- wpv-loop-end --&gt;
{{wpv-no-posts-found}}{{wpml-string context=&quot;wpv-views&quot;}}&lt;strong&gt;No posts found&lt;/strong&gt;{{/wpml-string}}{{/wpv-no-posts-found}}
{{wpv-layout-end}}
[/code]</ta_ignore>

Save the View.
<h2>5. Insert Your Views</h2>
The Views should display on your <strong>homepage</strong> and in the <strong>sidebar</strong>.

First of all, let&rsquo;s insert the shortcodes into your homepage. Navigate to Pages and <strong>edit your homepage</strong> &ndash; this should be the page set to your static front page under Settings &gt; Reading.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3583" title="edit page" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/editpage.png" alt="an image of the magazine front page listed on the WordPress back end. The mouse hovers over the edit button" />

To insert a View you will need to <strong>add the correct shortcode</strong>. Click on the Views icon and select <strong>Categories View</strong> and <strong>Slider View</strong>.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3583" title="insert views shortcodes" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/insertviewsshortcode.png" alt="a screenshot of the insert views shortcode popup with Categories View and Slider View highlighted" />

You can also <strong>add some text around the shortcodes</strong> if you want.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3583" title="text area" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/pageshortcodes.png" alt="an image of the page text area with the two shortcodes and a sentence that says 'welcome to the Views magazine'" />

<strong>Update your page.</strong>

Next, you need to add a <strong>widget </strong>to your sidebar. Navigate to <strong>Appearance &gt; Widgets</strong>.

<strong>Drag the WP Views widget to the sidebar</strong> and select the Sidebar View from the dropdown. You can give the widget a title if you want.

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3583" title="widget" src="http://wp-types.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/widget.png" alt="an image of the WP Views widget" />

Save your widget.

Your WordPress Magazine Theme is now ready! And you haven&rsquo;t written one line of code!

All you&rsquo;ve got to do is add some content. Remember that if a post is to appear in the slider you should add a magazine image to the custom field on the post admin page.

<a href="http://ref.wp-types.com/magazine">Check out our example to see how yours should look!</a>
